BLM invites comment on proposed solar project in Nevadawww.blm.gov/press-release/blm-invites-comment-proposed-solar-project-nevadaLAS VEGAS ‚Äì The Bureau of Land Management welcomes public comment on the draft environmental analysis for a new clean energy project proposed on approximately 2,433 acres of BLM-managed public land about 38 miles west of Las Vegas, adjacent to the Clark and Nye County line.

If approved, the Rough Hat Clark County Solar Project would add 400 megawatts of clean solar photovoltaic power to the grid, enough to power over 74,000 homes.¬†The proposed project would also include a 700-megawatt battery energy storage system.¬†

‚ÄúPublic input on this Draft Resource Management Plan Amendment and Environmental Impact Statement is critical as we continue to evaluate the proposed project,‚Äù said BLM Las Vegas Field Manager Bruce Sillitoe. ‚ÄúThe most useful comments concern the scope of the environmental impact statement analysis, potential alternatives, and identification of relevant information and studies.‚Äù¬†

The efficient deployment of renewable energy from our nation‚Äôs public lands is crucial in achieving the Biden-Harris administration‚Äôs goal of a carbon pollution-free power sector by 2035, as well as Congress‚Äô direction in the Energy Act of 2020 to permit 25 gigawatts of solar, wind, and geothermal production on public lands no later than 2025.

The BLM is currently processing 67 utility-scale onshore clean energy projects proposed on public lands in the western United States. This includes solar, wind, and geothermal projects, as well as gen-tie lines that are vital to clean energy projects proposed on non-federal land. These projects have the combined potential to add more than 37 gigawatts of renewable energy to the western electric grid. The BLM is also undertaking the preliminary review of over 195 applications for solar and wind development, as well as 97 applications for solar and wind energy site area testing.

BLM will host one virtual and one in-person public meeting to discuss the Rough Hat Project:¬†

In-person meeting in Pahrump, Nevada, on January 30, 2024, 6-8 p.m. PT at the Pahrump Nugget Hotel and Casino, 681 NV-160, Pahrump, NV 89048.
Virtual meeting on February 1, 2024, 6-8 p.m. PT. Register on the project‚Äôs BLM National NEPA Register page.
Written comments may be mailed to the BLM Southern Nevada District Office, Attn: Rough Hat Clark County Solar Project, 4701 N. Torrey Pines Drive, Las Vegas, NV, 89130 or emailed to BLM_NV_SND_EnergyProjects@blm.gov. Comments may also be submitted using the ‚ÄúParticipate Now‚Äù function at the BLM National NEPA Register project page.¬†

The 90-day comment period will close April 11, 2024. For more information, please contact Whitney Wirthlin, Project Manager, at 725-249-3318 or email BLM_NV_SND_EnergyProjects@blm.gov.

Imagine someone taking your data and using it to permeate everything you do online.  Buy a lamp on Amazon, and DIY shows fill your streaming playlists.  Pick up a kid from school and your car begins playing kid-friendly songs.  Buy an OTC hemorrhoid cream, and your laptop and tablet get bookmarks for colon cancer screening kits.What if all these privacy invading tactics were collated into one sweeping term?  What if the tech industry called all of this "magic"?  It clearly isn't.  And nothing about it really is magic, just creepy.  Asking Magic to do what people would regard as a magic outcome doesn't work 90% of the time.  But everyone in the country is calling it magic.  There are entire industries grabbing onto magic, kids sidetracking their prior studies in college from Programming and Data Science to get on to Magic Science.  Because there's more money in it.And everything under the sun is appending Magic to their products: toasters, cars, toothbrushes, medical devices, intimate products... It's not enough to get a "dumb" Sex Toy, those have all left the market thanks to industry collusion (there's a demand for them, but all the top industry manufacturers agreed to stop making them and acquire/close smaller competitors who try to do it anyway.)  Magic Sex Toys are all that are left.What about previous conceptions of magic? Fire from thin air, wisps of light floating above you, turning a vegetable into a horse drawn carriage?  Nope.  This is magic now.  What that is needs to be called something else.  Or it's the realm of a child's imagination and laughed off as being cute, while future programs, books, games and other products fall in line with the new definition.  So the next generation of kids bolster the new reality of magic and dismiss the nonsensical prior one. An entire lexicon is developed. Privacy is an illusion, but magic is now real. Spells are just code.  Enchantments are devices that are infused with magic to mysteriously behave to the consumer but fall in line with Magic principles and rules those same consumers shall never know. And those same kids who grew up surrounded by magic become politicians, lawyers and professors who teach Magic, litigate in favor of it, and pass laws on the pro-Magic paradigm.  Opponents are discredited as luddites and opportunists seeking to undermine Magic for their own gain. (When they are doing anything but.) It doesn't need a long term timeline, just 20 years is enough to cement magic into reality.  Same as the Internet.This is why AI pisses me off.  Replace AI with Magic and privacy with Intellectual Property and it's what we're seeing now.
